Preliminars

As usual, we start setting up the working directory

setwd ("E:/OTHER ACADEMICS/PROYECTOS COVID 19/PROYECTOS DATOS ASCOFAPSI/project_ascofapsi_2020")

Loading the required packages

pacman::p_load(tidyverse, dplyr, summarytools, ggplot2, readxl, corrplot, knitr)

and uploading the data base in a new data frame called ascofapsi

ascofapsi <- read_excel("base de datos limpia.xlsx")

Variables

For this exploratory analysis, variables were divided in three sets: predictors (demographics, costs and utilities, motives), mediators (personality, self-eficacy and intentions) and dependent measures (covid prevention behaviors). (see file XXXXX)

Descriptive summary

print(dfSummary(ascofapsi, graph.magnif = 0.75), method = 'render')

Some keypoints of the descriptive summary

n= 926

Worsening in physical activity, sleep habits, economy, job. Slight worsening in social relationships. Improvement in hobbies. Near to normal in familiar relationships (I expected an improvement) Neutral in relationships with neighbors.

Most of the participants are females (76.5%), from Bogot (39.6%), with university studies (97%), students (36.3%) or employees in the private sector (48.4%).

In general, there are medium correlations between variables measuring perceived self-efficacy to adopt covid prevention behaviors and variables measuring the adoption of such kind of behaviors. Then, it is interesting to ask about a comparison between the effect of self-efficacy and intention over the adoption of covid prevention behaviors. But, the correlation analysis seems to advert that neither intentions and self-efficacy are good predictors of covid prevention behaviors, which may be useful, for example, in order to evaluate initiatives that promote prevention behaviors appealing to these constructs.
